Loading the ADLINK EC GPIO Driver:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	Follow below commands to load the driver:
	# sudo insmod driver/adl-bmc.ko 
        # sudo insmod driver/adl-bmc-gpio.ko

Exporting GPIO Pins:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	After loading the driver, a new entry will be created. Please check below path:
	# ls /sys/class/gpio/
	export  gpiochip504  unexport
	
	In the above, gpiochip504 is the new entry. Here the number 504 is considered as base. 
	
	Exporting gpio pins:
	<switch to root user>
	# su
	# echo 504 > /sys/class/gpio/export     <EC GPIO 0>
	# echo 505 > /sys/class/gpio/export  
	# echo 506 > /sys/class/gpio/export 
	# echo 507 > /sys/class/gpio/export 
	# echo 508 > /sys/class/gpio/export 
	# echo 509 > /sys/class/gpio/export 
	# echo 510 > /sys/class/gpio/export 				
	# echo 511 > /sys/class/gpio/export      <EC GPIO 7>

Setting the Direction of GPIO pins:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	Setting as input:
	# echo in > /sys/class/gpio/gpio511/direction    <EC GPIO 7>
	Setting as output:
	# echo out > /sys/class/gpio/gpio511/direction   <EC GPIO 7>

Writing value for GPIO which is configured as output:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	Making it high:
	# echo 1 > /sys/class/gpio/gpio504/value         <EC GPIO 0>
	Making it low:
	# echo 0 > /sys/class/gpio/gpio504/value         <EC GPIO 0>
	
Reading value of GPIO pin which is configured as input:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	# cat /sys/class/gpio/gpio504/value


	


